        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between Edge Computing and a CDN?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A CDN primarily caches static assets (images, CSS, JS) at locations close to users. Edge computing goes a step further by executing custom backend logic (JavaScript, Wasm) at those same locations, eliminating the round trip to a central origin server."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are Edge functions the same as Serverless functions (AWS Lambda)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "They are similar in that you don't manage servers, but they differ in runtime. AWS Lambda runs Node.js processes in specific regions, which introduces cold starts. Edge functions use the V8 isolates engine, running globally with near-zero cold starts."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I connect to a database from the Edge?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, but with caveats. Traditional databases (like Postgres) use stateful TCP connections, which struggle with thousands of global Edge connections. Edge computing relies on HTTP-based databases, Edge-native DBs (like Cloudflare D1), or specialized connection poolers."
        }
      }
